	<video youtube="5y9oHu5_2_4"><description>An introduction to momentum.</description></video>

		<definition>
	<title>Momentum</title>
	<statement>
		<p></p>
		<p>The <term>momentum</term> of a single object is defined as the mass of the object times its velocity: <me>\vec{p} = m\vec{v}</me>
		For a system with multiple objects, the momenta of each object in the system can be summed: <me>\vec{p}_{system} = \Sigma \vec{p}_i = \vec{p}_1 + \vec{p}_2 + \vec{p}_3 + \dots</me></p>
	</statement>
</definition>


<exercise xml:id="x_summarize-momentum">
			<title>Summarize What You Learned - Momentum</title>
			<p></p>
			  <p>Write a 1-2 sentence description of what the definition of momentum says in words. </p>
			</exercise>
			<exercise>
			<title>Sensemaking: Units</title>
			 <statement>
				<p></p>
			  <p>What are the units of momentum?</p>
				</statement>
				<answer>
				<p>kg m/s</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
			<exercise>
			<title>Sensemaking: Direction</title>
			<statement>
				<p></p>
			  <p>Unlike energy, momentum is a vector quantity.  In what direction does the momentum for a single object point?  Explain your reasoning.</p>
				</statement>
				<answer>
				<p>The momentum for a single object always points in the same direction as the object's velocity!</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
			<exercise>
			<title>Calculation</title>
			<statement>
				<p></p>
			  <p>Estimate the magnitude of the momentum of a car traveling down a highway.</p>
				</statement>
											<answer>
							<p>I estimated around 37,200 kg m/s.  (Many cars have a mass that is somewhere around 1200 kg, and a typical highway speed limit is 70 mph, which is about 31 m/s.)</p>
							</answer>
			</exercise>
